Teacher Retention Study Overview

Data was collected across 273 school districts in Kansas to understand the key factors that drive teacher retention. Starting the Summer of 2021, this project has been funded by the KASB, KBA, and Emporia State University. There is the potential to perform more in-depth analyses and support but please contact Dr. Bret Church or Dr. Luke Simmering if you’d like to discuss options. Options include custom benchmarks to compare to similar districts (i.e., location, size, etc.) as well as more inferential analysis to predict which factors are the most significant drivers of retention and engagement. Advisory support is also available to collaboratively develop goals and action plans to engage and retain teachers within your particular district. Survey metrics can be used to track engagement and/or retention over time in order to provide evidence regarding interventions.

Interpretation Guidance

Items were evaluated on a 5-point Likert scale to assess the extent to which they aligned with the presented area and/or aspect of teaching.

  • Retention Factor Measurement

  • A set of 38 items were developed to evaluate the extent to which factors impact their perceived importance to continuing as a teacher Teacher Engagement Measurement

  • A standard set of 11 items were developed to measure overall ‘engagement’ of each individual teacher within (and across) school districts. Satisfaction Factors:

  • A standard set of 12 items were developed to gauge the extent to which aspects of teaching are related to their general satisfaction with

  • Additional Analysis and Service Options

  • Data Review Session (1-hour review with researcher(s) to review data in more detail)

  • Custom benchmark (select up to 10 districts to compare your data)

  • Strategy Matrix (more in-depth analyses to build detailed recommendations)
